label: Severe or very severe pneumonia eligibility
definition: Severe pneumonia was defined as cough or difficulty breathing with lower chest wall indrawing. Very severe pneumonia was defined as cough or difficulty breathing and at least one of the following signs: central cyanosis, difficulty breastfeeding or drinking, vomiting everything, multiple or prolonged convulsions, lethargy or unconsciousness, or head nodding.

label: Multiple or prolonged convulsions
definition: Multiple defined as 2 or more episodes. Prolonged defined as 15 or more minutes in duration. Only collected for cases. Observed by clinician at admission to inform eligibility status.

label: Very severe pneumonia
definition: Only relevant for cases.

label: Chest indrawing and wheezing
definition: Only collected for cases with evidence of chest wall indrawing without pneumonia danger signs. Observed by clinician at admission to inform eligibility status.

definition: Fully vaccinated defined as 1) 3 doses, or 2) 2 doses if the child was 12 months or older at receipt or the doses were given at least 8 weeks apart for a child less than 9 months, or 3) 1 dose if age at any dose or child's age at introduction was 24 months or older. Partially vaccinated defined as 1 or 2 doses, unless fell into above catch-up categories.

label: Fully vaccinated for pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV)
definition: Fully vaccinated for PCV. For children younger than 1 year, full vaccination was defined as having received at least one dose and being up to date for age on the basis of the child's age at enrollment, doses received, and country schedule (allowing a 4-week window for each dose); for children aged 1 year or older in all sites except Kenya, full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses; for children older than 1 year in Kenya (which introduced PCV with catch-up campaign), full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses, two doses if given at least 8 weeks apart and the child was older than 1 year of age at first dose, and one dose if the child was older than 2 years at any dose or at introduction.
codebookDescription: Fully vaccinated for PCV. For children younger than 1 year, full vaccination was defined as having received at least one dose and being up to date for age on the basis of the child's age at enrollment, doses received, and country schedule (allowing a 4-week window for each dose); for children aged 1 year or older in all sites except Kenya, full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses; for children older than 1 year in Kenya (which introduced PCV with catch-up campaign), full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses, two doses if given at least 8 weeks apart and the child was older than 1 year of age at first dose, and one dose if the child was older than 2 years at any dose or at introduction.

definition: Common colonizers defined as CMV, H. influenzae, M. pneumoniae, Moraxella species, S. pneumoniae, and S. aureus. Klebsiella pneumoniae was considered a contaminant due to difficulties with assay specificity. For "absolute qPCR" variables, the sample was considered positive if above the qPCR density thresholds (see PERCH publications). H. influenzae - 5.9 log10 copies/mL, S. pneumoniae 6.9 log10 copies/mL.

label: Virus in nasopharyngeal/oropharyngeal swabs
definition: Common colonizer defined as CMV. Measles testing was only performed on cases who met the clinical criteria for measles testing (history of measles in past month, measles rash, measles admission diagnosis, measles discharge diagnosis). "Absolute qPCR" variables were considered positive if above the qPCR density thresholds (see PERCH publications). CMV - 4.9 log10 copies/mL.
